{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601676/1937123101/0283.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR\nWith Sunday Morning Edition\nTHEODORE W. NOYES, Editor\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nFRIDAY_December 31, 19J7\n\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company\nMain Office: 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Offlre: 110 East 42nd St.\nChicago Office: 4,15 North Michigan Ave.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014City and Suburban\nRegular Edition\nEvening and Sunday-Hoc per mo. or 15c per week\nThe Evening Siar_45c per mo. or me per week\nThe Sunday Star_ .5c per copy\nNight Final Edition\nN1?ht Final and Sunday Star _10c per month\nNight Final Star 55c per mouth\nCollection made at the end of each month or\neach week. Orders may be sent by mail or tele\nphone National 5000\nRate by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance\nMaryland and Virginia\nORlly and Sunday_1 yr., $10.00; 1 mo., Hoc\nDaily only -1 yr., $K.OO; 1 mo., ftoc\nSunday only.._1 yr.. $4.00; 1 mo., 40c\nAll Other Slates and Canada\nDaily and Sunday.1 yr.. $12.00; 1 mo., 51.00\nDaily only -1 yr., $s.00; 1 mo., 15c\nSunday only-1 yr.. 55.00; 1 mo\u201e 5oc\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\nthe use lor republication ot all news dispatches\ncredited to it or not otherwise credited in this\nphper and also (he local news published herein.\nAll rights of publication of special dispatches\nherein also are reserved.\n\\^hieh Tax to Choose.\nAs between the two tax programs pro\nposed to the Commissioners, one of them\nrepresenting the views of a committee\nof taxpayers chosen by the Commis\nsioners to advise them, the other repre\nsenting the views of a few officeholders\nat the District Building, the taxpayers\u2019\nproposal is by far the more reasonable,\nthe more logical and the most produc\ntive of assured revenue.\nThe difference between the two pro\ngrams may be boiled down to this:\nThe citizens' committee proposed\nabolishing (by failure to re-enact itl the\nbusiness privilege tax; proposed a sales\ntax and left to the Commissioners, as\nprovided by law, the fixing of a real\nestate tax rate at the beginning of the\nnext fiscal year that would raise the\nnecessary balance.\nThe officeholders proposed the same\nStep with relation to the business priv\nilege tax; expressed a pious hope for a\n$1.50 real estate tax rate, and proposed, in\naddition, a one pier cent income tax and\na one per cent sales tax.\n.Bom committees were united on a\n\u2022trong plea, the justice of which is\nobvious, for an increase in the Federal\npayment to the District, which is, of\ncourse, the place where all considera\ntions of additional taxation should begin.\nThe Commissioners should accept the\nrecommendation of the citizens\u2019 tax\ncommittee and throw overboard the pro\nposals of the officeholders\u2019 commmittee.\nThis latter committee was at least partly\nresponsible for the hodge-podge tax\nprogram enacted during the past ses\nsion, including the unfair and unwork\nable business privilege tax. It showed,\nby its performance last spring, that it\nwill hop one way as quickly as it will hop\nanother. It blows hot and then blows\ncold and then blow's hot again on every\nconceivable form of tax that can be\nsuggested. By next week it will doubt\nless change its mind and propose another\ntax program.\nIf the Commissioners are &ise they\nwill insist, first, that the lump sum pay\nment be increased in some proportion to\nthe increased local tax burden and the\nincreased revenue demands of the Cap\nital. They will accept the recommenda\ntion of the citizens\u2019 committee and join\nwholeheartedly in the proposition that\nif additional local tax revenue is neces\nsary\u2014which is probable\u2014a selected sales\ntax be enacted in the District, as\nIt has been enacted in the majority of\nthe States, as the most equitable as well\nas the most practical method of raising\nadditional local revenue.\nine proposal, again, of a small local\nIncome tax is ill-advised. As shown last\nyear, constitutional questions in connec\ntion with such a tax in the District are\nimportant enough to raise serious doubt\nas to the validity of the tax. If the tax\nis equitable, it must apply to members\nof Congress as well to the great number\nof District residents who claim legal resi\ndence elsewhere. If applied equitably\nIn principle\u2014taxing everybody whose in\ncome is earned in the District, including\nCongressmen\u2014the results of the tax will\nbe. in practice, inequitable. And to pro\npose a small local income tax at a time\nwhen Congress is gradually approaching\nthe inevitable step of lowering Federal\nexemptions and taxing small incomes\nwhich now escape, in addition to raising\nrates on -others, is simply asking for\nanother dose, in peculiarly bitter form,\nof double taxation.\nThe real test of a patriot is his ability\nto go on saying \"Happy New Year!\u201d\nwhile looking at the picture pages from\nEastern Asia.\n1937.\nSensitive men and women found much\nIn the year 1937 to mourn. The twelve\nmonths span was rife with tragedy for\nentire nations, indeed for the whole\nworld. War in Spain and in China;\npolitical strife in Russia, France, Ru\nmania and other countries; dictatorship\nwith inevitable traduction of civic liberty\nin Italy and Germany; racial dissension\nIn the Holy Land; strikes and labor\nturmoil in the United States\u2014day by\nday reports of these troubles have made\nsorry reading for millions.\nMore than the usual quota of catas\ntrophes were written into the chronicle\n\u2022f human experience. The great diri\nfible Hindenburg crashed in flames, a\n\u2022chool in Texas was destroyed by\nan explosion which cost the lives of hun\ndreds of little children, costly floods\nswept the Ohio and Mississippi Valleys.\nMeanwhile, poverty and crime and traffic\naccidents took toll of the race in terri\ntories theoretically fortunate.\nFamous personalities who departed\nfrom the earthly scene Included: John\nr\nD. Rockefeller, sr.; Andrew W. Mellon,\nFrank B. Kellogg, Newton D. Baker,\nJoseph B. Robinson, Elihu Root, Sir\nAusten Chamberlain, Larz Anderson,\nPhilip Snowden, John Drinkwater,\nAlbert Bigelow Paine, Norman Hapgood,\nRollo Ogden, George Gershwin, Edith\nWharton, Sir James Matthew Barrie,\nCharles Lathrop Pack, John Russell\nPope, Anna Hempstead Branch, Thomas\nG. Masaryk, Ellis Parker Butler, Osgood\nPerkins, Ogden Mills, George Horace\nLorimer, Mrs. Leslie Carter, Sir John\nston Forbes Robertson, John Franklin\nJameson, Edward A. Filene, James Ram\nsay MacDonald, Guglielmo Marconi, E.\nW. Howe, William Alanson White, Robert\nWorth Bingham and a numerous com\npany of helpful and useful individuals\nwho may have been less famous but prob\nably were as deeply loved.\nThe \u201cfront page\u201d stories of the year\nsometimes, of course, were reasonably\ncheerful. In New York the American\nLegion staged a convention which had\nmany comic aspects, and in London King\nGeorge VI and Queen Elizabeth were\ncrowned in a pageant of solemn beauty\nand impressiveness. President Roose\nvelt's second inauguration was spoiled\nby a cloudburst which continued from\nmorn till night, and his effort to \u201creform\u201d\nthe Supreme Court ended in burlesque.\nThe popularity of the New Deal declined\nwith a new depression and the disclosure\nthat vast Federal spending had not really\n\u201cprimed the pump\u201d of recovery.\nBut it may be that it is as yet too early\nto judge 1937 accurately. There may\nhave been victories for humanity which\nwere not publicized, gains which cannot\nbe appraised in their present develop\nment. As 1938 begins, it will be a uni\nversal hope that peace may be restored,\nprosperity retrieved and the ^jpcies\ngranted a breathing spell from misery\nand grief difficult to comprehend or\nunderstand.\nErin Go Bragh!\nEnd of the old year and dawn of the\nnew bring momentous changes to that\nlittle patch of green in the Atlantic\nOcean, known since 1922 as the Irish\nFree State, but henceforward named\nIreland in English and Eire in Gaelic.\nThe alteration synchronizes with the\nformal enforcement of the new constitu\ntion, which marks one more stage in\nthe realization of the nation's dream of\ncomplete independence of the British\ncrown.\nFor all practical purposes, that status\nis achieved. Ireland is already a re\npublic in all but name. The oath of\nallegiance to Great Britain is abolished.\nThe office of governor general, the fic\ntion by which the King at London pre\ntended still to rule in Dublin, is no more\nLand annuities, pledged under the act\nof union establishing the now defunct\nFree State, are no longer paid. Ireland\nis a full-fledged member of the League\nof Nations. As the maintenance of her\nown legation and the presence of her\nrespected Minister to the United States,\nMr. MacWhite, attest, the Dublin gov\nernment exercises autonomous diplo\nmatic authority\u2014classic evidence to all\nthe world that Ireland is master in her\nown house as well as of her external\naffairs.\nWhen the new constitution on Wed\nnesday became the supreme law, the\nname of the King of England and of\n\"his majesty's government in Ireland\"\nautomatically disappeared. In character\nistically temperamental terms, the obli\nteration is hailed by the Dublin press\nas \u2018removing forever Britain's dark\nblighting shadow.\" In a transatlantic\nradio address Mr. de Valera indicated\nthat his cup of happiness will not be\nquite full until the \u2018\u2018British shadow\u201d is\nalso taken from Ulster, the northern por\ntion of Ireland still loyal to \u201cthe mother\ncountry.\u201d To make the new constitution\nembrace \u201cthe whole of the national ter\nritory,\u201d the Prime Minister summons \u201cthe\nIrish race to dedicate itself anew.\u201d\nUnperturbed by this clarion call, the\nLondon government contents itself with\na legalistic protest against the claim that\nNorth Ireland also must eventually be\nruled from Dublin. With approval of\nthe dominions, it is quietly declared that\nthe British commonwealth of nations\n\u201ctakes note\u201d of the Irish constitution,\nand is \u201cprepared to treat it as not effect\ning a fundamental alteration in the\nposition of the Irish Free State, in the\nfuture to be described under the new\ninstrument as \u2018Eire\u2019 or \u2018Ireland,\u2019 as a\nmember of the commonwealth.\u201d\nWhether it rules all or only part of\nthe Emerald Isle, the American people,\nrichly leavened with the seed of the old\nsod, wish new Ireland an abundance of\nprosperity and contentment in its\nsovereign incarnation.\nIf years incapacitate a man for a hard\njob some of the leading citizens of the\nJapanese government should be required\nto explain why they are still active.\nProduce the Evidence.\nThe legal profession has a rule of\nethics\u2014often honored in the breach\u2014\nwhich makes it unethical for a lawyer\nto \u201ctry his case in the newspapers.\u201d The\npurpose of the rule is to secure the im\npartiality of the Jury by preventing at\ntorneys from reaching the minds of\nprospective jurors through the news\npapers with inflammatory and irrelevant\nmaterial that would never pass muster\nas evidence in court. The circumven\ntion of this rule by many practlctioners\nhas contributed materially to current\ncriticisms of the profession and has\nbeen a source of considerable concern to\nthose leaders of the bar who have been\nstriving to elevate the standards of the\nlaw and the who practice it.\nNeedless to say, they will receive little\ncomfort from the recent speech of As\nsistant Attorney General Robert H.\nJackson criticizing \u201cmonopolists\" and\n\u201cbig business.\u201d Mr. Jackson heads the\nanti-trust division of the Department of\nJustice, and there have been numerous\nundenied reports that his assignment to\nthat post was preliminary to an extensive\ncampaign against monopolies by the\ni\nGovernment. The whole tenor of his\ntalk strengthened the belief that addi\ntional litigation against monopolists is\nabout to be instituted, and, if that be\ncorrect, the Assistant Attorney General,\nholder of a high position of public trust,\nshould refrain from the use of the radio\nor the newspapers to build up his case\nin advance of trial.\nThis is not to suggest that Mr. Jack\nson and other officials charged with en\nforcement of the anti-trust laws should\npull any punches in dealing with unlaw\nful monopolistic practices they may find\nto exist. The juggling and maintenance\nof unnaturally higher prices through\nmonopolies is forbidden by law and that\nlaw should be enforced. There is, how\never, in this country a more fundamental\nlaw\u2014namely, that every man is entitled\nto a fair trial by an impartial jury.\nIf Mr. Jackson has any evidence of\nthe existence of monopolies he should\nproduce it before the proper tribunal and\nproceed at once with litigation to elimi\nnate them. In that endeavor he can be\nassured of public support. But in the\nmeantime he should refrain from vitriolic\npublic addresses, in the nature of po\nlitical campaign speeches, which indis\ncriminately smear all business and are\nat best of dubious service to the attain\nment of what should be his primary ob\njective\u2014the enforcement of the law in a\nmanner compatible with the dignity of\nhis position.\nThe Japanese Emperor is still repre\nsented as studying what has happened\nand the world has at least been con\nvinced of his consciousness that it\nmust not happen again. Custom is strong\nand the voice of Tiny Tim speaks with\nout uncertainty in the demand, \"God\nbless us, every one.\" No better word of\naltruism has been written. It should\nbe more widely translated.\nWhen an old American humorist passes\nfrom the scene there is scant politeness\nto his memory although there may be\na reproachful query as to why he did\nnot show Louis Ludlow's ability to com\nbine low comedy with the highest art of\nthe statesman.\nCharming weddings are noted among\nthe events of the social season In Wash\nington, D. C. The world is still gracious\nand listens with respect to what Cupid\nmay have to say, even amid the boister\nous illiteracies of Mars.\nEnormous calculations will be made\nnecessary if it becomes the duty of\nmathematicians and geologists to esti\nmate the mineral values that may have\nbeen covered up in the course of modern\nimprovements.\nOne of the favorite characters of the\nlate Don Marquis was \"Archie the Cock\nroach,\" not easy to forget, yet not always\ninspiring in its suggestion of human\nrelationships.\nPictures are important. Those which\ncome from the Yang-tse-Kiang are\nworthy of deliberate consideration by\nthis Government, though not of hasty\naction.\nTravelers have often reported strange\nand .interesting observations of condi\ntions in Russia. They are still doing so.\nShooting Stars.\nBY PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nCherished Drama.\nId like to see a good old-fashioned play\nAbout the boy who wandered far away,\nAnd when the landlord threatened heart\nless harm,\nCame home and paid the mortgage off\nthe farm.\nI'm weary of the stories of the lad\nWho swiftly goes entirely to the bad\u2014\nWho, somehow, got into a fearful twist\nAnd hollers for a psychoanalyst.\nFor he is only one against the throng\nWho love their home folks and do not\ngo wrong.\nWhere is the play so full of native charm\nIn which Jack paid the mortgage off the\nfarm?\n_\nPolitician and Statesman.\n\u201cAre you a politician or a statesman?\"\n\u2022\u25a0Both,\" answered Senator Sorghum.\n\u201cIn order to gain any positive influence\nas a statesman you are obliged some\ntimes to assert yourself as a politician.\u201d\nJud Tunkins says many a man is\ntempted to love dumb animals simply\nbecause they can't talk back.\nFavored Locomotive.\nOld locomotive! Whistlin\u2019 long and gay.\nSeemed so very happy as he traveled on\nhis way.\nHas abundant fuel. Has enough to drink.\nHas his wants all satisfied, and doesn't\nneed to think.\nA Political Power.\n\u201cIs your wife a power in politics?\u201d\n\"To a great extent,\u201d answered Mr.\nMeekton. \u201cIn addition to her own vote\nshe dictates mine, and, as the family\ngrows up, she will control several more.\u201d\n\u201cOnly an ungenerous mind,\u201d said Hi\nHo, the sage of ChiAatown, \u201cspeaks with\nout hesitation what it believes to be the\ntruth.\u201d\nMechanical Optimism.\nOh, keep on smiling every day!\nArrange your face for glad display,\nAnd strive, to keep from seeming sad,\nTo look Just like a dental ad.\n\u201cDe world, as it keeps movin\u2019,\u201d said\nUncle Eben, \u201cgives us de wily kind of\na free ride we has any reason to hope\nfor.\u201d\nDangerous Animals.\nProm the Cleveland Plain Dealer.\nNew Jersey motorists have been\nwarned of the danger of encountering\ndeer on the highway at night. Down\nhere people need not fear these animals\nas much as wolves, howling at their\ndoor*\na a\nTHE POLITICAL I\nMILL\nBY G. GOULD LINCOLN.\nA political new year is just around the\ncorner. What it holds for the Demo\ncratic New Deal party, for the still stag\ngering G. O. P. and the new but bellig\nerent American Labor party is still to\nbe developed. Two major scenes of action\nwill serve for the play of politics\u2014the\n1938 congressional and gubernatorial\nelections and the third session of the\nSeventy-fifth Congress.\nAs the session of Congress is about to\nopen on Monday administration\nspokesmen have unleashed a new attack\non business\u2014big business\u2014as the insti\ngator of the business recession. They\ncontend that it is all a part of a con\nspiracy to defeat the Roosevelt legisla\ntive program and to discredit the New\nDeal. It is no secret that many business\nmen have been opposed to the adminis\ntration\u2014not only during the last six\nmonths but for several years. Columns\nand columns have been written about\nit. Many business men have so de\nclared themselves. But now some of\nthe New Dealers see something secret\nin this opposition. They are charging a\nconspiracy. The business men saV, on the\nother hand, if there is any conspiracy\nit is on the part of the New Dealers to\nknock down business. The monopolies\nof the future, they say, will be govern\nmttital monopolies, politically controlled.\n\nWhen President Roosevelt sent a mes\nsage to the Congress at the opening of\nthe special session on November 15 last,\nhis message was regarded as conciliatory\n\u2014a holding out of the olive branch. He\nhas continued to hold many conferences\nwith important men in business and in\ndustry, discussing plans for meeting and\novercoming the recession in business.\nWhat will be the tenor of his address to\nthe Confess \"on the state of the Union\u201d\nwhen he delivers it at 1:30 p.m. Monday?\nWill he deal with the foreign situation,\nwhich has been tense, to say the least,\nas well as with the domestic situation?\nIt may be expected that he will, although\nthere has been no statement whatever\nregarding the message. Will he discuss\nmonopolies and the need for their curb\nand will he outline a program of legis\nlation?\nIf the President follows along the line\ntaken by Assistant Attorney General\nRobert H. Jackson and Secretary Harold\nL. Ickes of the Interior Department in\nhis discussion of the business recession,\nthe fur will fly again. To many it seems\nincredible that Mr. Jackson and Secre\ntary Icke6 would make the kind of state\nments with regard to business they have\nmade if such statements were not ap\nproved by the President. It is no secret\nthat many Democrats have been aroused\nby these repeated attacks on business at\na time when they believe that the ad\nministration should do what it can to\nencourage business.\n\nIn some quarters there is a growing\nopinion, however, that the President and\nsome of his advisers have come to the\nconclusion that the recession is not as\nbad as it has been pictured and that it\nwill not be of long duration. At the\nsame time, some of the critics of the\nadministration are asserting that the\nPresident and his advisers are merely\nseeking an alibi when they attack busi\nness for the failure of New Deal meas\nures to bring the \u201cmore abundant life.\u201d\n\nA day or two ago at his home in Clin\nton, Mass.. Senator David I. Walsh. New\nEngland Democrat, was caustic in his\ncriticism of the administration and its\ndealings with business. Walsh declared\nthat the administration might well have\ncome to the aid of business during the\nspecial session which closed just before\nChristmas, instead of seeking to drive\nthrough a program of reform legislation.\n\"There was a widespread belief, partic\nularly in business circles.\u201d said Senator\nWalsh, \u201cthat we should devote some time\nand attention to the business recession\nthat has developed rapidly since mid\nsummer. There was a disposition on the\npart of many members of Congress to\nseek a solution and extend some reme\ndies that were generally recognized as\nnecessary. It is difficult to state just\nwhat are the causes that resulted in the\npresent marked recession in business.\nIn my opinion, they are many. It is\ndue to an accumulation of policies that\nhave caused a general lack of confidence\non the part of capital and business in\ngeneral.\u201d\nSenator Walsh added that undoubtedly\nthe continuing failure of the Govern\nment to balance the budget, the rapid\naccumulation of a tremendous national\ndebt, certain unsound and burdensome\ntaxes and various laws which have\ngreatly increased the cost of production\nhave caused a general lack of confidence.\nHe joined with these causes of dis\ncouragement the unsettled labor condi\ntions. Rightly or wrongly, he said, busi\nness is frightened. \u201cIn my opinion,\u201d he\ncontinued, \u201cwhat is mo6t needed is an\nassurance of confidence that can come\nonly from the Federal Government.\u201d\n\nThis explanation of the business reces\nsion by Senator Walsh is vastly different\nfrom that now advanced by the admin\nistration spokesmen. His position, how\never, is that of a considerable number\nof Democratic members of Congress, and\nof many Democrats outside of Congress.\nIt is clear that if the administration,\nthrough the President himself, makes\na new drive against business, the division*\namong the Democrats may become more\nand more marked. Also the Jacksons and\nthe Ickeses are likely to have a tough\ntime convincing hard-headed Americans\nthat business has been torn down by\nbusiness men themselves for the mere\npurpose of getting rid of the New Deal.\nGenerally speaking, business is perfectly\nwilling to go right ahead making profits\nunder any political administration, if it\nbelieves that profits can be made.\nThe coming session of Congress, what\nit does and what it fails to do, and how\nit. reacts to the recommendations of the\nPresident, looms large indeed in the\npolitical panorama of the coming year.\nThe session may prove a great battle\nground, as has been predicted by Senator\nBurke of Nebraska, another Democrat\nwho opposes the New Deal in some im\nportant particulars.\n\nWhat is done or not done in Congress\nwill have its effects, too, on the congres\nsional elections. Ever since 1932, when\nthe Democrats swept the country\u2014in\ndeed, ever since 1930 when they won\ncontrol of the House of Representatives,\nthe Democratic party has continued to\nincrease its hold upon Congress. Each\nelection has shown a larger Democratic\nmajority in the House and in the Senate.\nIn the Senate only sixteen Republicans\nremain in the membership of ninety\nsix. In the House the Democrats out\nnumber the Republicans more than three\nto one. Unless the G. O. P. can make\nsome gains, can recapture many of the\nseats it formerly held in Congress, the\nfate of the G. O. P. seems to be sealed.\nThe country will seek some new organ\nization as a minority protest against the\nNew Deal party. As each new congres\nsional election has come along, the Re\npublicans have confidently predicted\nthey would regain lost ground. But in\neach case they have been mistaken. They\nhave lost more ground. This coming\nyear, however, due to internal troubles\nof the Democrats themselves, the Re\n\nTHIS AND THAT\nBY CHARLES E. TRACEWELL.\nIt was a record Christmas, literally,\nfor a great many peoj^.\nPhonograph records, of course.\nThey took the place of books, even of\nneckties, those old standbys.\nEspecially as gifts to men.\nWomen love music, but men love the\nrecords thereof.\nGo to the music stores, which have\nenjoyed a vast increase in this business\nduring the past two years, and note who\nare in the booths listening to records.\nThree out of four will be men.\nThere is something about recorded\nmusic which makes an especial hit with\nthe so-called stronger sex.\nPerhaps it is the mechanical marvel\nof it. Here on a disc are imprinted, in\ngrooves only six one-thousandth of an\ninch thick, the immortal music of the\nmasters.\nElectrical recording and reproduction\nhave made the process even more won\nderful than of old, and since its dis\ncovery it has been one of the true mar\nvels of the world.\n\nMany a man who, on past Christmases,\nreceived dozens of books, this Christmas\nfound a table filled with records.\nRecords in albums, mostly, for there\nis a \"feer' about the album and its en\nclosed discs which is eminently satis\nfying.\n\u201cInfinite riches in a little room\u201d is a\nquotation which fits exactly.\nIt is possible to hold in the hands an\nentire symphony, note for note.\nNo one in any other age has been able\nto do this.\n\nThe marvel of it will not down.\nPerhaps men, as a class, keep this\nwonder uppermost, that is why the\nrecords make such a gigantic appeal to\nthem.\nThose among them who love books\nwill find an album of some classic work\na most appealing substitute.\nIt is safe to say that those who re\nceived records, in lieu of books, did not\nmiss the latter for once in their lives.\nA Christmas without books had\nseemed impossible, until the virulent\nform of record admiration came Into\nbeing.\nOne always had admired the discs,\nbut it must be confessed that the old\nones had never been like these new\nones.\nNor could best of the old acoustical\nmachines, playing the best of the old\nacoustical recordings, give forth such\nmusic.\n\nElectricity, which some believe is the\nsecret of life, itself, is surely the genius\nbehind the newer recordings and ma\nchines.\nThose who may have placed their old\nmachines in the basement, and lost their\nInterest in the records as the result of\nradio's invasion, have a new excitement\nin life coming to them when their in\nterest comes into being again.\nEvery one who goes through this ex\nperience goes through it in exactly the\nsame way, so it may be expedient to\ndetail It, so that the symptoms may be\nknown beforehand.\nThe old machine, the old records\u2014\nyes, one had one, one had many of the\ndiscs.\nYes, one knew all about that.\nThey were all down in the basement,\nor maybe had been given away years ago.\nOne day a friend intrigues one into a\nrecord shop, just to listen to a new tune.\nThe new machines are grand, there\nIs no doubt of it: the records sound fine\non them. But the virus has not gone\ndeep, vet.\nTime is necessary for the incubation.\nOne day a decision is made to get a\nnew record. Why, it is the first time in\nten years!\n\nThe old machine is brought out of the\nbasement.\nThe new record sounds very good on\nit. One grudgingly admits it a little\nbetter.\nInterest grows.\nA few more records are purchased.\nOne says, with a lordly air, that it is\nimpossible to re-capture an old interest.\nThen, one day. a record which sounds\nexceptionally fine in the booth is brought\nhome, and put on the old machine.\nThe difference is apparent.\nUsually it takes just one record to do\nthis.\nOne man in this town is known to\nhave called up the store and ordered a\nnew machine the moment he got home.\n\nThe new machine brings out all the\ndepth, the sonority, the real music, which\nelectricity engraves in the new discs.\nOne suddenly realizes that this is the\nreal thing.\nThousands of people had found it out\nyears ago, but until this newer wisdom\nsuddenly descends upon one, it has no\nmeaning for the individual. It is like\nall true knowledge, it must come as a\nconversion.\nOne now knows that this music is the\nreal music, and that no one would be\nhappier to hear it than the master of\nold who wrote it.\nBeethoven, mightiest of masters, would\nhave loved this.\nWas it not he who helped Maelzel with\nhis mechanical organ?\n\nThe booklover who at Christmas re\nceived many more records than books\nrealizes at last that these are books, too,\nin a new form, holding some of the\ngreatest thoughts of the race.\nThey are emotional thoughts, rather\nthan logical thoughts.\nThey came into being because words\nfailed.\nIf this had not been so. there would\nnever have been any music.\nMusic captures something in heart and\nmind and soul which words are power\nless to express, even in the hands of the\ngreat writers.\nThe modern gramophone and records\ncapture the music masters, and give them\nto us at home.\nTherefore we are thankful for a record\nChristmas, and grateful to those com\nposers. musicians, engineers, merchants\nand friends who gave it to us.\nWASHINGTON OBSERVATIONS\nBY FREDERIC WILLIAM WILE.\nWith high-caliber administration guns\nblazing away at big business with reck\nless fury, the old year fades out amid\ngrave anxiety over what betides for com\nmerce, industry and finance. This week's\nattacks by Assistant Attorney General\nJackson and Secretary Ickes plastered\nwith such epithets as \"aristocratic\nanarchists,\u201d \"corporate earls\u201d and \"ducal\neconomic-overlords\u201d are a foretaste of\nwhat may be expected when President\nRoosevelt himself unlimbers his own\nbatteries of rhetorical invective. White\nHouse fire will open with his personally\ndelivered message to Congress on Mon\nday. Less than a week later executive\nguns will bark again when P. D. R. ad\ndresses the Jackson Day dinner. Both\npresidential fusillades will be broadcast.\nThe fight to \"master\u201d business\u2014as Ickes\nlast night candidly epitomized the pur\npose of the second Roosevelt administra\ntion-will then be on. By every indica\ntion, the feud between the politicians\nand the \"wealthy tycoons\u201d (another\nIckesism) will be one of the fiercest in\ncontemporary American history. The\npity, from the country\u2019s standpoint, is\nthat while hostilities rage, business al\nmost certainly wall drift from bad to\nworse. Fear will not be banished, con\nfidence restored, or frightened capital\nreleased. The inevitable result can only\nbe more closed factories, greater unem\nployment, less and less purchasing power,\nand general aggravation of the reces\nsion.\nThese are anything but happy New\nYear thoughts, but they are iron facts\nwhich impel authorities like Col. Leonard\nP. Ayres of Cleveland to predict that\nthe present decline will reach bottom\nduring the first half of 1938 and that\nnext year's results will be generally poor,\nwith recovery far slower than the reces\nsion. Washington buzzes with theories\nas to the administration\u2019s reason for\nlambasting business at a moment when\neverybody except New Deal zealots\nthinks salve, not salt, is what the Nation\u2019s\neconomic wounds need. That the Roose\nveltians badly require an alibi for things\nnot having turned out \"the way we\nplanned them\u201d is the commonest ex\nplanation of the ferocity with which\nbusiness is to be pilloried and punished.\nMessrs. Jackson and Ickes were the\nPresident\u2019s fishing companions in Florida\nlast month. It's now plain as a pike\nstaff that the anti-capital crusade was\nplotted and prepared on that occasion.\nJackson, Mr. Roosevelt's reputed fair\nhaired boy for the New York governor\nship in 1938 and even for the presidency\nin 1940, was apparently told off to drag\nout the \"monopoly\u201d red herring as the\ncause of recession, while \"Honest Harold,\u201d\nmaster phrasemaker of the cabinet, was\nassigned the task of stigmatizing the\n\u201cmoneyed aristocracy of America, which\nconstitutes an even greater menace to\nour Institutions than would a titled class\nwith vintaged handles to their names\nand whose corporate tentacles\nstretch their strangling length Into every\nnook and cranny of the land.\u201d\n\nIt\u2019ll be interesting to see whether Con\ngress develops nerve enough to call men\nand things by their right names, in con\nnection with the vendetta against busi\nness. A third of the Senate and all of\nthe House are even more directly inter\nested in the 1938 congressional elections\nthan the New Deal high command,\nwhich shudders to think what may\nhappen to Democratic candidates in the\nmidst of an unchecked depression. Re\nsponsive to sentiment and conditions\n-v\npublicans appear to have a better chance\nof winning something.\nEspecially will the Democrats be hard\nhit if the American Labor party develops\nnationally and puts up candidates of Its\nown, instead of supporting Democratic\nnominees. What recently happened in\nNew York City when the Labor party\njoined with Republicans to down the\nTammany Democrats Is significant.\n\u00aba\nback home, as members of Congress al\nwavs are, it remains to be seen whether\nthey will point with pride to. or view\nwith alarm, the anti-business campaign\nabout to be launched. Neither house\nduring the carnival of futility known as\nthe special session revealed any enthusi\nasm for following blindly wherever the\nWhite House leads. It is. therefore, at\nleast problematical if new measures to\nharass timid capital and ailing industry\nwill appeal to vote-needing ladies and\ngentlemen on the Hill. They know at\nfirst hand the meaning of rising unem\nployment and languishing trade in vir\ntually every congressional district of the\nland. If the Capitol is still inspired by\nthe fighting spirit which repelled the\nassault on the Supreme Court, the ad\nministration may discover it started\nsomething it can\u2019t finish, with its drive\non business.\n\nThere must have been a time, some\ntwenty-five years ago, when Trust\nbuster Bob Jackson, now principal mata\ndor in the business bull-ring, thought\ndifferently about the minions and evils\nof capitalism. In those days, he not\nonly hobnobbed with \u201caristocratic anar\nchists.\u201d but was one of them. Soon after\nentering law practice at Jamestown, N.\nY., in 1913, Jackson became vice presi\ndent and general counsel of the local\nstreet railway company and of the\nJamestown. Westfield Northwestern\nRailroad. He was also a director and\ngeneral counsel of the Bank of James\ntown and the Jamestown Telephone\nCorp.\ni\nFederal Trade Commissioner Garland\n8. Ferguson will tomorrow establish a\nsecond new record. Now in his eleventh\nyear on that quasi-judicial body, he al\nready has the distinction of having serv\ned longer on it than any other commis\nsioner. On January 1, by rule of rota\ntion, Mr. Ferguson will become chairman\nfor the third time, a distinction no other\nF. T. C. member has ever enjoyed,\nthough a couple have served two chair\nmanship terms. The North Carolinian\nis a Democrat appointed in 1927 by\nPresident Coolidge and reappointed in\n1934 by President Roosevelt. Not more\nthan three of the five commissioners\nmay be of the same political party. Mr.\nFerguson was an Annapolis midshipman\nfor two years, preceding his graduation\nfrom the law school of the University of\nNorth Carolina in 1900.\n\nApropos the flooding of the country\nwith leaflets of the National Council\nfor the Prevention pf War, urging pres\nsure on members of Congress to support\nthe Ludlow war referendum, Washing\nton recalls some statistical disclosures\nof that restlessly active pacifist group\nat the end of its first decade, in 1931.\nExecutive Secretary Libby, reporting to\nthe council's annual meeting, declared:\n\u201cThe council is far stronger than it was\neven a year ago, for in the past twelve\nmonths it has remedied some of its chief\nweaknesses. It is now incorporated, for\none thing, and can receive bequests. The\nprivilege of exemption from taxation,\nextended to contributors for the amount\nof their donations, has been renewed,\nfollowing our incorporation. In 1929 and\nin 1930 we distributed from national\nheadquarters 2,000,000 pieces of litera\nture. This year the figure is nearly\n2,250,000. We have sent out 12,595 pack\nages, or more than 1.000 a month.\u201d\n\nSenator Carter Glass, who will be 80\nyears young on January 4, is the father\nof the Senate in point of age, but is out\nstripped in length of service by several\ncolleagues who are his juniors in vintage.\nThe Virginia veteran did not come to\nthe Senate until 1920. Borah of Idaho\n(72) came in 1907, Smith of South\nCarolina (73) in 1908. Ashurst of Arizona\n(63) and Pittman of Nevada (65) in\n1912, and Norris of Nebraska (76) in\n1913.\n(OMvrlsbt. 1M7.)\nft\nANSWERS TO\nQUESTIONS\nBY FREDERIC J. HA SKIN.\nA reader can get the answer to any\nquestion of fact by writing The Evening\nStar Information Bureau, Frederic J\nHaskin, director, Washington, D. C.\nPlease inclose stamp for reply.\nQ- Are there any American Army\ntroops in China?\u2014R. 8.\nA. The only American Army troops In\nChina are in the 15th Infantry at Tient\nsin, as part of the international patrol\nto keep the railway open from the coast\nto Peiping.\nQ. Do airliners carry parachutes for\npassengers?\u2014W. 8.\nA. They do not.\nQ. What is the number of Canadian\nborn people among the population of\nthe United States?\u2014B. H. B.\nA. At the time of the last census, the\nnumber of persons of Canadian birth in\nthe United States numbered 1,278,421.\nQ. What is the average speed of New\nYork subway trains?\u2014A. S. B.\nA. The average speed of express sub\nway trains in New York City is 25 miles\nper hour and for local subwav trains 15\nmiles per hour, both including station\nstops.\nQ. Is there any difference in the tem\nperature of the earth on the surface and\ntoward the core, and if there is. what\nfactors account for the difference?\u2014C.\nC. A.\nA. Borings into the earth's crust have\nrevealed the fact that temperature in\ncreases with depth. A recent statement\nof the Geophysical Laboratory of the\nCarnegie Institution of Washington is\nthat in the core of the earth the tem\nperature rises to 5,432 P. The core of\nthe earth is composed of metallic iron\nwith an alloy of nickel, and is so solid\nthat the pressure there is 47.000.000\npounds to the square inch. The enor\nmous pressure in a large measure ac\ncounts for the high temperature.\nQ. When has this country Issued\nmourning stamps?\u2014a. K.\nA. A Lincoln stamp in 1866, McKinlev\nstamp in 1922. Harding stamp in 1923\nand Wilson stamp in 192.6. Garfield re\nceived postal honors within a year after\nhis death, but the color of the stamp was\nbrown.\nQ. Next to President Roosevelt, what\nGovernment official at Washington has\nmade the most radio speeches?\u2014T. R. W.\nA. Secretary of Agriculture Henry A.\nWallace is the most frequent broad\ncaster in the Government, having been\non the air 22 times in 1937.\nQ. Does the Braille Institute of Amer\nica issue a monthly magazine in raised\ntype?\u2014H. L.\nA. It issues one in Braille and one\nin Moon type.\nQ. Who were the Basket Makers?\u2014\"\nP. F.\nA. They were one of the earliest peo\nples who inhabited Southwestern United\nStates and adjoining Mexico. They lived\nsome 1.000 years B. C. and made no\npottery.\nQ. What is a pyrrhic victory?\u2014C. W.\nA. It is a victory at grpat cost to thp\nvictors. Pyrrhus, king of Epirus, said,\nafter the victory at Asculum in 279 B\nC., \"One more such victory over the\nRomans and we are utterly undone.\" 1\nQ. How many people are employed In\nclass one railroads in the United States?\n\u2014R. H. G.\nA. Employes on class one railroads of\nthe United States, as of November, 1937,\ntotaled 1.060,296.\nQ. How long did it take Noah to build\nthe ark?\u2014A. J. K.\nA. According to the Bible. 120 years\nelapsed between the time of God's warn\ning to Noah instructing him to build\nthe ark and the flood. It is stated also\nthat Noah while building the ark be\ncame a preacher of righteousness. It\nhas sometimes been advanced as a\ntheory that the word, years, might be\nmore properly translated month or moon.\nQ. What is the origin of the word,\ntenor?\u2014H. K. G.\nA. The name is derived from the Latin\ntenere, to hold, reflecting the medieval\ncustom of assigning the chief melodv\nor holding part to this voice.\nQ. Does much rain fall in Egypt?\u2014H.\nM.\nA. There is some rain near the Medi\nterranean; 100 miles from the sea. four\nor five showers a year; in upper Egypt\npractically no rain. The water of the\n^\u2018Ie system 0{ irrigation make\nthe Nile Valley fertile.\nQ. What were the contents of the old\ntime wassail bowl in England?_c. V\nA. The recipe which was most widtfy\npopular down to the eighteenth century\nconsisted of a mixture of warm ale with\ncream boiled with cloves and with the\nyolks of eggs beaten and stirred into it\nSops of bread, sugar and thick cream\nwere added as well as cinnamon, ginger\nand blanched almonds.\nQ How long will Senator Dixie Bibb\nGraves serve in the Senate?\u2014F. R. L.\nA. She will serve only until a primarv\nhas been held to determine the Demo\ncratic nominee. The Governor, her hus\nband, has stated that he will then ap\npoint the person who is nominated to\nserve until the election.\nQ. What are the most popular books\nin series among elementary school *tu-\u2019>\ndents?\u2014W. H.\nA. In a study of the reading interests\nof elementary school children it was\nfound that among boys the most popular\nbooks of the kind were the Tarzan series,\nthe Tom Swift books and the Bov Allies\nseries. The favorite books for girls were\nthe Bobbsey Twins series, the Nancy\nDrew series and Little Women. ,t\nQ. Was the man for whom the guil\nlotine was named an executioner?\u2014w. J.\nA. Joseph Ignace Guillotin. who sug\ngested this method of execution, was a\nFrench physician and a teacher in the\nJesuit College at Bordeaux.\nA Rhyme at Twilight\nBy\nGertrude Brooke Hamilton. w\nThe Wind\nI blow the snow in gusty whirls\nAnd great pines bend before me.\nThe while I pile high, drifting swirls\nAnd dare men to ignore me.\nO\u2019er rills and hills I sweep along,\nMy course forever seaward;\nA boat afloat hearing my song\nSets every sail to leeward.\nYet though my blow is loud and vasL.\nHurling things helter-skelter,\nI strive to drive by mighty blast\nI All wanderers to shelter.","height":"31352","width":"22572"}}
